Dims need verification

Important note on this work:  
I meant to send a different work than this with Aaron but there was a mix up as he was here rather late.  Not his fault at all - I wasn't clear in my communication.  
The only reason I wasn't quite ready to send the work is because there is some paper on the back  that is a bit exposed and I needed time to cover it with fiberglass to give it some reinforcement.  I also wanted to put a shallower cleat on the back, but the one that is on the back is totally fine.  It looks finished from the front, and I'm totally fine to show it.  If I can get my hands on it again, I'd like to give that paper more protection.  This would not take very long to do.

Title: Untitled (Bird)
Materials: digital video2 min. 21 sec.exhibition view, Simon Preston Gallery, New York
Notes / Exhibition Text: Simon Preston is delighted to present The First Rebellion is History, Next Week Rome Falls , a group exhibition of new work by gallery artists that celebrates the gallery‚Äôs four year anniversary.The exhibition‚Äôs title is borrowed from a recent series of photographs by Daniel Joseph Martinez. In each of his images, hand-groomed Bonsai trees, tended by the artist, are placed on pedestals in front of national flags, activating a rich set of connotations about nature, aesthetics and social control. Martinez will exhibit two further photographic series of works in his solo exhibition titled I want to go to Detroit; Cheerleaders CHEER at LAXART which opens on 4 February, as part of Pacific Standard Time in LA.Michelle Lopez exhibits a pair of hand- formed clay, wall-leaning sculptures that examine the iconography of the flag. Following the previous trajectory of her work titled Flare, properties of drawing invade the sculptures and expose a kind of natural, organic form.Jessica Mein will show a series of billboard works depicting construction sites. Through the artist‚Äôs obsessive hand-made perforations and collage, the mechanical printing process found in the discarded material is interrupted and altered.Marco Rios‚Äô Unititled photograph is hyperbolic in nature, employing humor and slapstick tactics to address the more solemn issues of failure, death, desire, and despair.Kara Tanaka has transformed a cowhide into an abstracted map by shaving and carving onto the skin, illustrating the search for both physical and mythical mountain systems. Tanaka‚Äôs use of animal hides draws a parallel to the Tibetan iconographic image of flayed skin as a symbol for the destruction of the ego.Caragh Thuring includes a large-scale diptych of a volcano. Painted on unprimed linen, with an extreme efficiency of marks, the volcano appears mythical or simply dormant and elicits a certain faith and desire in its mere existence, echoing the very foundation and method in the construction of each of her paintings.Josh Tonsfeldt will exhibit recent work made while on residency at the Zabludowicz Collection in Sarvisalo, Finland. He is included in New York: Directions, Points of Interest at Massimo de Carlo , which will open on January 25th ‚Äì March 24th in Milan.

Title: Untitled
Materials: Alligator hide, wood, acrylic glass, foamcore, matt board, inkjet print, framed photograph
Notes / Exhibition Text:
First exhibited at Art Basel Miami, 2010. 
Collected by Carlo Bronzini --> donated to Parrish Museum


Note to Franco Soffiantino: 
The hide of the sculpture is from an alligator my father hunted and killed in Louisiana several years ago.  It has since been on display in his home with many other hunting trophies.  I was particularly drawn to this object because of its large size, its headlessness, and the intensity of the thickness and heavyness of the skin.  Moreso than any other stuffed and hunted animal, it feels like an abstracted body, almost alien.  I think the black color of the skin adds to this unfamiliarity and strangeness of the object.  I am not particularly against hunting, but the desire to skin and stuff bodies and put them on display is a kind of ritual of masculinity that is odd to me.  This object is already a sculpture, a totem of masculinity and virilty and violence.  What I needed to do with this object in my work is simple - give it a lightness and sense of melancholy,  slightly recompose the body, distort it and elevate it from the floor.  I have chosen thin wooden beams to form the armature.  One central beam structure props up the middle of the body, and there are also two picture frames made from the same material.  One frame is taken apart and the glass, matt board and paper fan out in a semicircle around the right side of the body, coming out from what was the right rear leg.  The glass, board and paper are all gently resting against one another.  On the other side is a complete frame, also made of the same wood.  It is under the middle if the gators body.  The frame is empty except for a few fragments of a photograph.  The frames may relate to the alligators body - empty shells.  They also merge with its body, giving it a new sort of skeletal structure.  The use of the wooden beams also relates conceptually to the piece i did in my show at your gallery.  The wood is used as a kind of drawing tool, a crude tracing of a space while embedded within the space it is representing - in the first case the gallery and in this case the dead animal's body.
